The paper deals with the construction of reliable spanners, which are a fundamental data structure in distributed computing and network design. The paper uses techniques from computational geometry, graph theory, and randomized algorithms. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CG (Computational Geometry), and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis). The paper also involves probabilistic analysis, which suggests the sub-category cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper presents a new construction technique, which involves skip-lists, a well-known data structure in computer science, suggesting the sub-category cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics).
